 social inclusion and equality, have played a part in shaping the nature of current initiatives. The Politics of Social Inclusion and Labor Representation concludes that we need to appreciate the complexity of trade-union traditions, established paths to renewal, and competing trajectories of solidarity. While trade union organizations remain wedded to specific trajectories, trade union renewal remains an innovative, if at times, problematic and complex set of choices and aspirations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign workerszGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aForeign workerszNetherlandsxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aForeign workerszSpainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aImmigrantszEuropean Union countriesxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aImmigrantszGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aImmigrantszNetherlandsxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aImmigrantszSpainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aLabor unionszGreat Britain. 0aLabor unionszNetherlands. 0aLabor unionszSpain. 0aMinority labor union memberszGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aMinority labor union memberszNetherlandsxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aMinority labor union memberszSpainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 4aEurope. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aimmigration, labor movements, captalism, trade union.1 aHyman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarino, Stefania, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMartínez Lucio, Miguel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK 